ent of border thinking to the rest of the world, as well as the importation of ideas to the border itself. Beginning with site-specific conceptual artwork of the 1980s, particularly the performances of the Border Art Workshop/Taller de Arte Fronterizo, Sheren shows how these works reconfigured the border as an active site. Sheren moves on to examine artists such as Guillermo Gómez-Peña, Coco Fusco, and Marcos Ramirez “ERRE.” Although Sheren places emphasis on the Chicano movement and its art production, this groundbreaking book suggests possibilities for the expansion of the concept of portability to contemporary art projects beyond the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszMexican-American Border RegionxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszMexican-American Border RegionxHistoryy21st century. 0aBoundaries in art. 0aPerformance artzMexican-American Border Regiony20th century. 0aPerformance artzMexican-American Border Regiony21st century. 7aART / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30226240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477302279423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477302279/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK